        "paragraph_index": 0,
        "text": "Short answer up front (qualitative, pending constants): to suppress Ca²⁺ while retaining Cu²⁺ in solution, the most practical ligands are fluoride and condensed phosphates (pyro-/tripolyphosphate). These preferentially sequester/precipitate Ca²⁺ relative to Cu²⁺ under mild aqueous conditions. Avoid carboxylates (citrate, oxalate, tartrate) and aminopolycarboxylates (EDTA, NTA), which bind Cu²⁺ strongly and will compromise Cu²⁺ measurement.",
