      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "| Ligand (family) | Ca²⁺ vs Cu²⁺ (qualitative) | Practical note |\n|---|---|---|\n| Fluoride (F⁻) | Strongly favors Ca²⁺ (CaF₂ readily forms/limits Ca²⁺ activity); comparatively weak Cu²⁺ complexation in water | Commonly used to “mask” Ca²⁺ by precipitation while Cu²⁺ remains measurable in solution (control pH/ionic strength to avoid HF formation and glass attack) |\n| Condensed phosphates (pyrophosphate, tripolyphosphate) | High Ca²⁺ affinity; generally lower Cu²⁺ affinity than for alkaline earths | Widely used water softeners; effective Ca²⁺ sequestration without strongly tying up Cu²⁺; verify with your method’s pH/ionic strength |\n| Silicate | Preferential Ca²⁺ uptake/precipitation; limited Cu²⁺ complexation | Can reduce Ca²⁺ activity; may gel/polymerize at high pH—control conditions |\n| Borate | Forms calcium borates more readily than copper borates | Works at alkaline pH; ensure your method tolerates high pH/borate |\n| Sulfate | Can reduce free Ca²⁺ via CaSO₄(s) under some conditions; CuSO₄ remains soluble | Selectivity is modest and highly condition-dependent; less reliable than F⁻ or polyphosphates |\n| Gluconate / lactate | Moderate Ca²⁺ complexation; Cu²⁺ also complexes | Selectivity is limited; not ideal if Cu²⁺ must remain fully free/available |",
