        "paragraph_index": 4,
        "text": "Operational tips\n- Decide whether you want to “mask” by precipitation (e.g., CaF₂) or by complexation (e.g., polyphosphates). Precipitation is often simpler for Ca²⁺ and less likely to affect Cu²⁺.\n- Keep conditions consistent (pH 4–7 and low ionic strength are common starting points for Cu²⁺ assays), and confirm that your analytical technique (e.g., AAS, ICP, voltammetry, colorimetry) tolerates the added ligand.\n- After masking, verify recovery of Cu²⁺ with a spike test; adjust ligand dose to fully suppress Ca²⁺ without impacting Cu²⁺ response.",
